<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,440,1080]" box="[199,1263,548,575]" pageId="9" pageNumber="136">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,369,548,575]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="136">
<typeStatus box="[199,369,548,575]" isOtherTypeStatus="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="136">Other material</typeStatus>
</emphasis>
. Same data as 
<typeStatus box="[537,638,549,575]" pageId="9" pageNumber="136">holotype</typeStatus>
, two specimens observed alive, and used for karyology.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,440,1080]" pageId="9" pageNumber="136">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,584,611]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="136">Etymology</emphasis>
. The species’ name honors Chico Mendes (
<date box="[822,1045,584,611]" pageId="9" pageNumber="136" value="1944-12-15">December 15, 1944</date>
– 
<date box="[1060,1290,585,611]" pageId="9" pageNumber="136" value="1988-12-22">December 22, 1988</date>
), a Brazilian environmentalist, who fought to preserve the Amazon rainforest, and was killed on the very day the 
<typeStatus box="[1262,1360,621,647]" pageId="9" pageNumber="136">holotype</typeStatus>
of this species was being studied.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,440,1080]" pageId="9" pageNumber="136">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,504,692,719]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="136">Description and Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Curini-Galletti &amp; Stocchino &amp; Norenburg" authorityYear="2019" box="[635,951,693,719]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Monocelididae" genus="Duplominona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="9" pageNumber="136" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="dissimilispina">
<emphasis box="[635,951,693,719]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="136">Duplominona dissimilispina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in habitus, arrangement of internal organs, number and position of genital pores (
<figureCitation box="[581,677,728,755]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1332,1357]" captionTargetBox="[159,1361,323,1298]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1437,345,1313]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 5. (A–C) Duplominona chicomendesi n. sp. (A) Habitus of a living animal; see Fig. 1 for interpretation of anatomical features. (B) Reconstruction of the inverted cirrus showing the sclerotised copulatory structures. (C) Micrograph of the inverted cirrus (Holotype). (D–G) Duplominona diademata n. sp. (D) Micrograph of a metaphasic plate. (E) Habitus of a living animal; see Fig. 1 for interpretation of anatomical features. (F, G) Reconstruction (F) and micrograph (G) of the inverted cirrus of the Holotype. (Scale bars: B–D = 5 m; F, G = 10m)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3371015/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="136">Fig. 5 A</figureCitation>
). Copulatory organ with a very small cirrus (
<figureCitation box="[1183,1316,728,755]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1332,1357]" captionTargetBox="[159,1361,323,1298]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1437,345,1313]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 5. (A–C) Duplominona chicomendesi n. sp. (A) Habitus of a living animal; see Fig. 1 for interpretation of anatomical features. (B) Reconstruction of the inverted cirrus showing the sclerotised copulatory structures. (C) Micrograph of the inverted cirrus (Holotype). (D–G) Duplominona diademata n. sp. (D) Micrograph of a metaphasic plate. (E) Habitus of a living animal; see Fig. 1 for interpretation of anatomical features. (F, G) Reconstruction (F) and micrograph (G) of the inverted cirrus of the Holotype. (Scale bars: B–D = 5 m; F, G = 10m)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3371015/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="136">Figs 5 B, C</figureCitation>
), with few spines arranged in 5–7 rows. Proximal spines are 3–5 μm in length, strongly curved, with a wide, flattened basis, to 3 μm in diameter. In the middle of cirrus, spines are longer, to 7.5 μm, even more curved, with a very slender distal tip. Distalmost spines are smaller, to 2 μm long, straighter, with a wide, flattened basis. Proximally, the cirrus lumen is surrounded by a furrowed pseudocuticula.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,440,1080]" box="[199,593,909,935]" pageId="9" pageNumber="136">Prostatoid stylet about 20 μm long.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,440,1080]" pageId="9" pageNumber="136">
<emphasis box="[199,323,945,971]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="136">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,316,945,971]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="136">Karyotype</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
With n=3, and basic karyotype for the 
<taxonomicName authority="(Curini-Galletti &amp; Martens, 1990)" authorityName="Curini-Galletti &amp; Martens" authorityYear="1990" baseAuthorityName="Curini-Galletti &amp; Martens" baseAuthorityYear="1990" box="[763,1323,945,971]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Monocelididae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="9" pageNumber="136" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="family">
Monocelididae (
<bibRefCitation author="Curini-Galletti, M. &amp; Martens, P. M." box="[946,1315,945,971]" pageId="9" pageNumber="136" pagination="255 - 261" refId="ref17375" refString="Curini-Galletti, M. &amp; Martens, P. M. (1990) Karyological and Ecological Evolution of the Monocelididae (Platyhelminthes, Proseriata). Marine Ecology, 11 (3), 255 - 261. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1439 - 0485.1990. tb 00243. x" type="journal article" year="1990">Curini-Galletti &amp; Martens, 1990</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
; Chromosome pairs I and II markedly differing in length. Karyotype formula: FN=5; Chromosome I: 51.58 ± 2.81; 46.11 ± 1.29 (m); Chromosome II: 33.45 ± 1.53; 45.85 ± 1.34 (m); Chromosome III: 14.95 ± 2.46; 8.11 ± 3.9 (a) (based on 6 plates).
</paragraph>
